node.text: “If you can only be tall, because somebody’s on their knees, then you have a serious problem.” PLEASE start your Sunday watching this incredible clip with Toni Morrison. Charlie Rose (ugh) initially asks Morrison if she still encounters racism, despite her success. She turns the question around, explaining how racism is the only tool white supremacists have to undermine Black people’s success. It’s a timely and powerful clip with useful framing for understanding and confronting white supremacist terror in 2021.

node.title: Toni Morrison On Race And Racism

Find the Betches Sup podcast on Spotify, or on iTunes via betches.co/suppod (we’ll have a swipe up in Stories)⁣

node.text: Where’s the line between celebrating femininity and falling into sexist tropes? Last month, Sup hosts sat down to discuss the question on all of our minds: is it sexist to stan Kamala Harris’s outfits? What do we signal to some women when we only celebrate others? Do we apply the same standard to women whose views we don’t agree with? It was a fascinating and cathartic conversation. Listen to the full episode at the link in bio/Stories betches.co/sexism

node.title: Is It Sexist To Stan Kamala Harris’s Outfits?

node.text:
Suni Lee of the United States has won gold in today’s individual all around event finals at the Tokyo Olympics! The Minnesota native got her start practicing on a wooden beam her dad built for her. In the past two years, COVID shut down her gym, she broke her foot, and lost two relatives to coronavirus. Lee is no stranger to competing under intense circumstances. In 2019, she medaled in the US championship right after her dad suffered a fall and became partially paralyzed. Lee is part of Minnesota’s Hmong community -- the largest community of about 260,000 people in the US. Her parents, John Lee and Yeev Thoj, fled Laos for Thailand when they were children before moving to Minnesota. 

Another thrilling moment this morning: Rebeca Andrade won silver, bringing home Brazil’s first ever Olympic medal in women’s artistic gymnastics 🇧🇷

node.text: Only eight gymnasts can compete in each event final at the Olympics and 24 in the all-around. But the “two per” rule means only two athletes can compete per country. Even with a few mistakes, Team USA qualified for the team finals, and its members qualified to participate in every single event final plus the all-around. Some members of Team USA performed better than competitors from other countries, but were excluded from event finals because of the rule. Simone Biles made some uncharacteristic mistakes but still qualified to the all-around final in first place. Listen to Pop Alarm with @dylanhafer for daily updates on all things Olympics 2020
